Predicting Monthly Sales for a Superstore

  • Anthony Blakley, 04/21/2024
  • Goal : The goal of this project is to build a regression model to predict monthly sales from a superstore. I will use Nearest Neighbors Regression to make my predictions. To evaluate the performance of my model, I use the evaluation: metric R-squared score.

Data Collection

  • Obtain the "Superstore Sales Dataset" from Kaggle and name it sales.csv.
    • This is a retail dataset of a global superstore for 4 years.
  • Read the dataset into a dataframe

df.drop(columns = dropping, inplace = True)

# tranform date to pandas datetime
df['Order Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Date'], format = '%d/%m/%Y')

# add month feature
df['month'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order Date']).dt.to_period('M')
In[10]:

Feature Selection and Data Preparation

In[13]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder

# aggregates the sales data solely on a monthly basis
monthly_sales = df.groupby('month')['Sales'].sum().reset_index()

'''
match rows between the two dataframes where the values in the 'month' column are the same
maintains the 'Sales' column name and makes a new column, 'Sales_monthly' 
representing the `monthly_sales_original` column
'''
df_merged = pd.merge(df, monthly_sales, on = 'month', suffixes = ('', '_monthly'))

# select predictor variables
variable_predictors = df_merged[predictors]

# select target variable
variable_target = df_merged['Sales_monthly']

In[15]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Split the data into training and temporary sets (80% for training + temporary)
x_train, x_temp, y_train, y_temp = train_test_split(
    variable_predictors,
    variable_target,
    test_size    = 0.2,  # 80% for training, 20% for temporary
    random_state = 0
)

# Split the temporary data into validation and testing sets (50% each)
x_validation, x_test, y_validation, y_test = train_test_split(
    x_temp,
    y_temp,
    test_size    = 0.5,  # 50% for validation, 50% for testing
    random_state = 0
)

# check the shapes of the training and testing sets
print("Shape of X_train:", x_train.shape)
print("Shape of y_train:", y_train.shape)
print("Shape of X_validation:", x_validation.shape)
print("Shape of y_validation:", y_validation.shape)
print("Shape of X_test:", x_test.shape)
print("Shape of y_test:", y_test.shape)

In[16]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder

'''
In one-hot encoding, each category is represented by a binary vector where only one bit is 
"hot" (set to 1), and all other bits are "cold" (set to 0). So, for the color "blue," which 
is the third category in our example, the binary vector would be [0, 0, 1].
'''

# One-hot encode categorical predictors (encodes any categorical predictors)
encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown = 'ignore')
x_train = encoder.fit_transform(x_train)
Original Color Encoded Red Encoded Green Encoded Blue
Red 1 0 0
Green 0 1 0
Blue 0 0 1

Model Development and Train

In[17]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor

# use 3 neighbors to predict the value, consider neighbors closer to the target more important (distance)
# using weights="uniform" (default) weighs all points equally
model = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors = 3, weights = "distance")

# compute and store the nearest neighbors of each training sample
model.fit(x_train, y_train)

Model Evaluation

  • predictions on the training set
  • predictions on the test set
  • predictions on the validation set
  • calculate R2 metric
In[18]:
# training set
y_train_pred = model.predict(x_train)

# test set
x_test_encoded = encoder.transform(x_test) # [ transform new data using same encoding scheme ]
y_test_pred = model.predict(x_test_encoded)

# validation set
x_validation_encoded = encoder.transform(x_validation)
y_validation_pred = model.predict(x_validation_encoded)
In[19]:
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

'''
An R-Squared value shows how well the model predicts the outcome of the dependent variable. 
R-Squared values range from 0 to 1.

An R-Squared value of 0 means that the model explains or predicts 0% of the relationship 
between the dependent and independent variables. 
A value of 1 indicates that the model predicts 100% of the relationship.
'''

train_r2      = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred) 
test_r2       = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
validation_r2 = r2_score(y_validation, y_validation_pred)

print("Training    R-squared: ", train_r2)
print("Testing     R-squared: ", test_r2)
print("Validation  R-squared: ", validation_r2)

Training    R-squared:  1.0
Testing     R-squared:  0.9873650049153772
Validation  R-squared:  0.9831708628568755

Hyperparameter tuning analysis

  • illustrations for the model's performance gains
  • Model optimization progression
    • splitting data using 3 sets instead of 2
      • splitting using 80-10-10 instead of 80-20 & 70-30 (using two sets)
    • using a variation of predictors instead of the most influential one
    • using 3 neighbors vs 5 neighbors
    • distance weight instead of uniform
